article.description: Gerald Wallace scored 27 points and the Bobcats sent the Magic to their team-record 16th straight road loss.
article.headline: Wallace's 27 points lead Bobcats over Magic
article.linkText: Bobcats hand Magic 16th consecutive road defeat
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- After the Orlando Magic set a dubious team record, coach Brian Hill indicated changes could be on the way. Gerald Wallace scored 27 points and the Charlotte Bobcats sent the Magic to their team-record 16th straight road loss with a 108-102 victory on Tuesday night. Raymond Felton added 16 points and 13 assists and Primoz Brezec scored 22 for the second-year Bobcats, who snapped a four-game losing streak and won their 19th game, one more than all of last season. Hedo Turkoglu scored 24 points and Dwight Howard had 17 points and 15 rebounds for the Magic, who never led. Orlando, which hasn't won on the road since Jan. 26 at Philadelphia, broke the team record for consecutive road defeats set in the 1989-90 season. "I'm embarrassed by our performance," Hill said. "I hope our players are because they should be. The way we played proved we didn't respect the game or the team. We just went through the motions." The Magic cut a 20-point second-quarter deficit to 99-95 on Keyon Dooling's jumper with 1:35 left. But Jumaine Jones, who has hit at least one 3-pointer in 31 straight games, hit his third 3 on the next possession to make it 102-95. "You can't play one half of basketball and expect to win. You can't spot a team a 20-point lead," Hill said. "I'm going to have to decide whether we want to play the same people. The team we put out there tonight didn't want to play. If they don't want to play, we have to put someone else out there that does." The Bobcats were without starting point guard Brevin Knight, who has a sore groin. Felton moved from off guard to point guard and Alan Anderson made his first start at shooting guard. Forward Melvin Ely was a late scratch with a migraine headache. Felton took advantage of being at his natural position. While he made only four of 14 shots, he was 3-of-7 from 3-point range, had seven rebounds, and matched his career-high of 13 assists set Jan. 28 at Washington. Wallace thinks Felton's up-tempo style was what Charlotte needed. "It helps a lot because he's quick enough to get to the basket, pull up and shoot a jump shot and has great vision on the court," Wallace said. "When we were pushing the ball we pretty much did what we wanted to do on offense." The Bobcats opened the second quarter on a 12-4 run, capped by Felton's 3-pointer, to take a 47-30 lead. Felton's 3 with 3:46 left put the Bobcats ahead by 20. It was 69-51 at halftime. But Charlotte nearly let the lead slip away, as the Magic woke up in the second half. "We made it hard again," Bobcats coach Bernie Bickerstaff said, upset his team was barking at the officials in the third quarter. "We allow little things to take us out of it. We finally got regrouped and got our composure back, but we make it difficult on ourselves." The Magic got within 87-82 on Jameer Nelson's 3-pointer with 9:48 to play in the fourth. But Wallace, who was one point shy of his career high, responded with a basket in the lane that started a 7-2 run that got the lead back to 10. It was too much to overcome for the Magic, who lost in Charlotte for the first time in four tries and fell to 6-29 on the road. "We dug ourselves such a big ditch," Dooling said. "We tried to play our way out of it. We shouldn't have to do that."

Game notes
Orlando's DeShawn Stevenson dunked on Wallace midway through the second quarter and was called for a taunting technical foul. A minute later Wallace dunked off an alley-oop and also was called for a taunting technical. ... Bickerstaff will fly to Atlanta on Thursday to attend the NCAA Tournament regional semifinals. Last week Bickerstaff scouted NCAA games in Salt Lake City, Dallas and Philadelphia.
